  <static seed="20" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/Factoring/factoring30.pg">
    <statement><p>Find the greatest common factor of the following terms.</p>
<p><m>{7x^{17}y^{2}}</m>, <m>{-21x^{10}y^{9}}</m>, <m>{70x^{3}y^{12}}</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="19" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>7x^{3}y^{2}\hbox{ or }-7x^{3}y^{2}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>There are three things to look for in this problem:
<ul label="disc">
<li>
<p>the greatest common <em>numerical</em> factor is <m>7</m></p>
</li>
<li>
<p>the greatest common power of <m>x</m> is <m>x^{3}</m>, since it has the <em>lowest</em> exponent.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>the greatest common power of <m>y</m> is <m>y^{2}</m>, since it has the <em>lowest</em> exponent.</p>
</li>
</ul></p>
<p>The greatest common factor of the three terms is <m>{7x^{3}y^{2}\hbox{ or }-7x^{3}y^{2}}</m>.</p>
</solution>
